	abstract = {The head-related transfer function (HRTF) of the cat adds directionally{\textbackslash}ndependent energy minima to the amplitude spectrum of complex sounds.{\textbackslash}nThese spectral notches are a principal cue for the localization of{\textbackslash}nsound source elevation. Physiological evidence suggests that the{\textbackslash}ndorsal cochlear nucleus (DCN) plays a critical role in the brainstem{\textbackslash}nprocessing of this directional feature. Type O units in the central{\textbackslash}nnucleus of the inferior colliculus (ICC) are a primary target of{\textbackslash}nascending DCN projections and, therefore, may represent midbrain{\textbackslash}nspecializations for the auditory processing of spectral cues for{\textbackslash}nsound localization. Behavioral studies confirm a loss of sound orientation{\textbackslash}naccuracy when DCN projections to the inferior colliculus are surgically{\textbackslash}nlesioned. This study used simple analogs of HRTF notches to characterize{\textbackslash}nsingle-unit response patterns in the ICC of decerebrate cats that{\textbackslash}nmay contribute to the directional sensitivity of the brain's spectral{\textbackslash}nprocessing pathways. Manipulations of notch frequency and bandwidth{\textbackslash}ndemonstrated frequency-specific excitatory responses that have the{\textbackslash}ncapacity to encode HRTF-based cues for sound source location. These{\textbackslash}nresponse patterns were limited to type O units in the ICC and have{\textbackslash}nnot been observed for the projection neurons of the DCN. The unique{\textbackslash}nspectral integration properties of type O units suggest that DCN{\textbackslash}ninfluences are transformed into a more selective representation of{\textbackslash}nsound source location by a local convergence of wideband excitatory{\textbackslash}nand frequency-tuned inhibitory inputs.},
