	abstract = {On the walking legs of crayfish, Austropotamobius torrentium, arranged in tufts over the chela, are large (smooth) setae. Electrophysiological recordings have demonstrated the presence within them of bimodal neurons with highly sensitive and specific responses to vibration and to chemical stimuli. Vibration at frequencies up to ca 45 Hz elicited a single, synchronized action potential per pulse; at higher frequencies many pulses failed to elicit a potential. The chemical stimuli found to be effective were nicotinamide and related substances (KM 5×10-5 mol/l), and again the saturation frequency was about 45 imp/s. There were no discernible differences in amplitude, time course or duration between the action potentials elicited by chemical stimuli and those elicited by vibration. Particularly strong evidence that these neurons are genuinely bimodal is the finding that chemical stimuli can modulate the sensitivity to vibration and that vibration alters the threshold and magnitude of the response to chemical stimuli. © 1986 Springer-Verlag.},
