	abstract = {The essential features of the CSD method, as well as the basic arguments for interpreting its results, are reviewed. Most of the studies that applied the CSD method are briefly considered. One specific attempt to reveal complementary information from field potentials, and to relate them to the underlying single-unit activity is outlined. It is based on CSD data from the cat visual cortex. This specific example has been selected to illustrate the theoretical considerations, because the extraordinary wealth of anatomical and physiological facts known about this area allowed CSDs and neuronal activities to be related in great detail. Analogous studies of the pericruciate cortex, as well as a generalization of the findings from CSDs about the intracortical processing of primary afferent information is discussed. The relationships between EEG phenomena and intracortical CSDs and their similarities with primary evoked cortical activity are presented. Finally, the central aspects of the CSD method as a complement to anatomical and single-unit methods is summarized, and the uniformity of cortical activation as revealed by the comparison of different types of field potentials is stressed.},
